My training has shown me one truth quite clearly. No matter where you go in the world, poverty stimulates assimilation. Some adapt quicker than others, and adaptation seems to speed with access to resources, but this truth can’t be ignored. So to the friends that wish their children could just “be” Tanzanian rather than always “being from,” I say this. Your encouragement to cling to everything that is foreign, you lead by robbing within your children a sense of pride in their own heritage. To “Not Be” Tanzanian is bogus. Your children, in a slower culture with a slower time, still crave belonging.

Look back. What did you like most about Swaziland? Ask beautiful Jen Noblezada to sew Brit’s hippo mask. Get in your pajamas and go to the midnight Mother’s Day message for your girls, mamas on four continents, too far apart for the mere years you are in their lives. Send Flannery tiny treasures from each trip. Both girls are thinking about teaching English abroad. Both brought Africans back comforters. Simply my advice? Don’t wait to create a feeling of belonging for your children. Create it. Really, it starts by sending fatherless fathers to places like Swaziland
